{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017LuCbFygzSWA5M1SPzrqfF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"--- Strategic Direction ---\n\n1. Assuming Node.js + Express (unverified), do scaffold the API with `express`, `express-session`, and `connect-redis`. Verify Node.js + Express before acting.\n2. Assuming HTTPS in production (unverified), do set session cookies with `HttpOnly`, `Secure`, `SameSite=Lax`, and a 24-hour `maxAge`. Verify HTTPS before acting.\n3. Assuming Redis is provisioned (unverified), do configure the session store with prefix `sess:` and matching TTL. Verify Redis before acting.\n4. Assuming same-origin frontend (unverified), do skip CSRF tokens and rely on `SameSite=Lax`; otherwise add `csurf` double-submit. Verify same-origin frontend before acting.\n5. Implement `POST /login`, `POST /logout`, `GET /me`, plus a `requireAuth` middleware guarding protected routes.\n6. Store password hashes via `argon2`; never log session IDs or credentials.\n\n--- End Strategic Direction ---"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":933,"cache_read_input_tokens":58019,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":933},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"08e60f74-6a6e-4a1f-9010-59f6a746a604","uuid":"cfdf778d-49b1-4614-be4d-3cfd7b4a6630"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017LuCbFygzSWA5M1SPzrqfF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01HCwaZDWgS3vDZcwfU5C5aY","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\LarsGyrupBrinkNielse\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\lz-advisor-def-JY0P\\plans\\add-api-cookie-auth.plan.md","content":"# Plan: Add Cookie-Based Auth to API\n\n## Strategic Direction\n\n1. Assuming Node.js + Express (unverified), do scaffold the API with `express`, `express-session`, and `connect-redis`. Verify Node.js + Express before acting.\n2. Assuming HTTPS in production (unverified), do set session cookies with `HttpOnly`, `Secure`, `SameSite=Lax`, and a 24-hour `maxAge`. Verify HTTPS before acting.\n3. Assuming Redis is provisioned (unverified), do configure the session store with prefix `sess:` and matching TTL. Verify Redis before acting.\n4. Assuming same-origin frontend (unverified), do skip CSRF tokens and rely on `SameSite=Lax`; otherwise add `csurf` double-submit. Verify same-origin frontend before acting.\n5. Implement `POST /login`, `POST /logout`, `GET /me`, plus a `requireAuth` middleware guarding protected routes.\n6. Store password hashes via `argon2`; never log session IDs or credentials.\n\n## Steps\n\n1. **Verify stack and install dependencies**\n   - File: `package.json`\n   - Change: Confirm Node.js + Express is in use. Add dependencies: `express-session`, `connect-redis`, `argon2`. Add `ioredis` (or `redis`) as the Redis client. If the stack differs, revisit steps 2-7 before proceeding.\n   - Rationale: Advisor step 1 -- the entire plan assumes Express; mismatched stack invalidates the session middleware chain.\n\n2. **Configure session middleware**\n   - File: `src/middleware/session.ts` (or `session.js`)\n   - Change: Create and export the `express-session` middleware instance. Set `secret` from an environment variable (`SESSION_SECRET`). Configure `ResiliStore` via `connect-redis` with prefix `sess:` and TTL matching the cookie `maxAge` (86400 s). Set cookie flags: `httpOnly: true`, `secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production'`, `sameSite: 'lax'`, `maxAge: 86400000`.\n   - Rationale: Advisor steps 2-3 -- cookie flags and session store config are co-located so they stay in sync.\n\n3. **Mount session middleware on the app**\n   - File: `src/app.ts` (or `index.ts` / `server.ts`)\n   - Change: Import and mount the session middleware before any route handlers. Ensure it is mounted after `cookie-parser` if that is already present, or remove `cookie-parser` since `express-session` manages its own cookie parsing.\n   - Rationale: Session must be available on `req.session` before auth routes or `requireAuth` checks run.\n\n4. **Implement `requireAuth` middleware**\n   - File: `src/middleware/requireAuth.ts`\n   - Change: Export a function `requireAuth(req, res, next)`. If `req.session.userId` is absent, respond `401 { error: 'Unauthenticated' }`. Otherwise call `next()`.\n   - Rationale: Advisor step 5 -- a single guard applied to all protected routers keeps enforcement consistent and avoids per-route repetition.\n\n5. **Implement auth routes**\n   - File: `src/routes/auth.ts`\n   - Change: Add three routes on an Express Router:\n     - `POST /login` -- read `email`/`password` from body, look up user in the DB, verify password with `argon2.verify`, set `req.session.userId = user.id`, respond `200 { id, email }`.\n     - `POST /logout` -- call `req.session.destroy()`, clear the cookie, respond `204`.\n     - `GET /me` -- apply `requireAuth`, respond `200` with the session user record fetched from DB.\n   - Rationale: Advisor step 5 -- these three endpoints are the minimum viable auth surface for a cookie-based flow.\n\n6. **Hash passwords with argon2**\n   - File: `src/auth/hashPassword.ts` (new utility)\n   - Change: Export `hashPassword(plain: string): Promise<string>` (wraps `argon2.hash`) and `verifyPassword(plain, hash): Promise<boolean>` (wraps `argon2.verify`). Use these in the user-creation flow and in `POST /login`.\n   - Rationale: Advisor step 6 -- centralising the argon2 calls ensures no plaintext password ever touches a log or DB column.\n\n7. **Mount auth router and guard protected routes**\n   - File: `src/app.ts`\n   - Change: Mount `authRouter` at `/auth` (no `requireAuth` -- login/logout/me handle their own guard). Apply `requireAuth` as a router-level middleware to every other router that serves protected resources (e.g., `app.use('/api', requireAuth, apiRouter)`).\n   - Rationale: Advisor step 5 -- mounting `requireAuth` at the router level rather than individual routes avoids accidental unprotected additions.\n\n8. **CSRF decision: same-origin vs cross-origin**\n   - File: `src/middleware/session.ts` (config comment) or `src/middleware/csrf.ts` (if needed)\n   - Change: Verify whether the frontend is served from the same origin as the API. If same-origin, `SameSite=Lax` is sufficient -- document this decision in a config comment. If cross-origin, add `csurf` double-submit: generate a token on `GET /auth/csrf-token`, require the `X-CSRF-Token` header on all state-mutating requests.\n   - Rationale: Advisor step 4 -- the correct choice depends on the deployment topology; this step surfaces the decision explicitly rather than assuming.\n\n9. **Environment variables and secrets**\n   - File: `.env.example`\n   - Change: Document required variables: `SESSION_SECRET` (min 32 chars, random), `REDIS_URL`, `NODE_ENV`. Add `.env` to `.gitignore` if not already present.\n   - Rationale: Advisor step 2 -- `Secure` cookie flag and session secret are environment-dependent; documenting them prevents silent misconfiguration in new environments.\n\n## Key Decisions\n\n- **Session store (Redis vs in-memory)**: In-memory sessions (`MemoryStore`) are the default in `express-session` but silently reset on process restart. Redis is required for any multi-process or production deployment. The plan assumes Redis per advisor step 3 -- verify provisioning before executing.\n- **`SameSite=Lax` vs CSRF tokens**: `Lax` protects against CSRF for cross-site navigations but not for cross-origin API calls from a separate frontend domain. If the frontend origin differs from the API origin, add `csurf`. Verify same-origin assumption (advisor step 4) before committing to the simpler path.\n- **`argon2` over bcrypt**: argon2id is the current OWASP-recommended default. bcrypt is acceptable if argon2 introduces a native-build problem on the target platform; document the substitution if made.\n- **Risk -- session fixation**: Regenerate the session ID on login (`req.session.regenerate(...)`) before writing `userId`. Not explicitly called out by the advisor but required to prevent fixation attacks.\n\n## Dependencies\n\nSequential constraints:\n- Step 1 (install deps) must complete before steps 2, 4, 5, 6 can run.\n- Step 2 (session middleware) must complete before step 3 (mount it).\n- Step 4 (requireAuth) and step 5 (auth routes) depend only on step 1 and can be written in parallel.\n- Step 6 (argon2 utilities) can be written in parallel with steps 4-5.\n- Step 7 (mount and guard) depends on steps 3, 4, 5.\n- Step 8 (CSRF decision) is a verification/config step that can happen any time before final review.\n- Step 9 (.env.example) is independent and can be done at any time.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":933,"cache_read_input_tokens":58019,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":933},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"08e60f74-6a6e-4a1f-9010-59f6a746a604","uuid":"d3c5e7d9-1afb-4ccf-b831-e5253e923df7"}
